<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-19T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-19T04:00:00-05:00" n="40" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/15963: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-19T18:00:00+09:00">June 19, 1940—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 19—6:03 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>471. Continuing my 470, June 19, 5 p.m.</p>
                        <p>2. I have an appointment later this afternoon with the Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs and I propose to ask him as on my own initiative whether
                            the Japanese Government is aware of and associates itself with the
                            position taken by the Japanese Army as above reported. Craigie
                            authorizes me to use this information but without revealing individual
                            Japanese source.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>